00:00:20.822 --> 00:00:22.530
ELIZABETH CHOE:
Assessment for this class

00:00:22.530 --> 00:00:26.560
was probably the hardest
thing for me, at least.

00:00:26.560 --> 00:00:29.220
How to assign a fair
grade to students, because

00:00:29.220 --> 00:00:31.732
at the end of the day,
they're a grade for this.

00:00:31.732 --> 00:00:33.940
And it wasn't going to be
an A for effort type thing.

00:00:37.630 --> 00:00:39.910
It was actually really
hard because anything

00:00:39.910 --> 00:00:44.690
that requires creative effort--
I talked to you about this

00:00:44.690 --> 00:00:46.540
for a long time-- you
don't want to crap

00:00:46.540 --> 00:00:49.560
on people's creative efforts,
even if it's just not

00:00:49.560 --> 00:00:50.720
very good.

00:00:50.720 --> 00:00:52.404
CHRIS BOEBEL: It's very hard.

00:00:52.404 --> 00:00:54.570
ELIZABETH CHOE: Jamie and
I talked a lot about this.

00:00:54.570 --> 00:00:59.220
But initially, the rubric was
very plastic elements based.

00:00:59.220 --> 00:01:03.190
Like, is this well lit,
can you hear the audio OK?

00:01:03.190 --> 00:01:05.560
And we just kind of scrapped
that, and really went

00:01:05.560 --> 00:01:12.140
with-- there were four sort
of principles to the class

00:01:12.140 --> 00:01:16.660
that I talked about on the
first day, which was spark,

00:01:16.660 --> 00:01:19.230
does it foster curiosity,
and that was like a big theme

00:01:19.230 --> 00:01:20.980
that went through every
single assignment,

00:01:20.980 --> 00:01:23.560
and how it manifested change
assignment to assignment.

00:01:23.560 --> 00:01:26.539
You can see on the rubric.

00:01:26.539 --> 00:01:27.330
Kill your darlings.

00:01:27.330 --> 00:01:30.687
Like, is it concise enough.

00:01:30.687 --> 00:01:31.770
There are a couple others.

00:01:31.770 --> 00:01:35.740
So that's how we
approached grading.

00:01:35.740 --> 00:01:40.440
And we assigned them
raw numerical scores,

00:01:40.440 --> 00:01:45.180
and we didn't have like, an
A is 20, a B is 10, or 15.

00:01:45.180 --> 00:01:53.630
It was in progress was from 0
to 5, and steps moving forward

00:01:53.630 --> 00:01:58.670
was like five to 10, and then
mastery was like 10 to 15,

00:01:58.670 --> 00:01:59.540
for instance.

00:01:59.540 --> 00:02:01.440
So they would get
numerical grade feedback.

00:02:04.140 --> 00:02:07.770
We gave a lot of weight
to their daily reflections

00:02:07.770 --> 00:02:13.870
so that not everyone in the
class would end up with a C.

00:02:13.870 --> 00:02:15.300
GEORGE ZAIDAN: I
have a question.

00:02:15.300 --> 00:02:18.090
Do you think grading should
have been A for effort?

00:02:18.090 --> 00:02:21.690
Because in real life, and
I didn't tell this to you

00:02:21.690 --> 00:02:23.850
when we were planning the
course, and I'm sorry.

00:02:23.850 --> 00:02:27.470
But in real life, it
almost is A for effort.

00:02:27.470 --> 00:02:32.730
If I show up to do voice over
and I'm late and I'm sloppy,

00:02:32.730 --> 00:02:35.470
and I don't do a
very good job, I'm

00:02:35.470 --> 00:02:38.740
not going to get hired again.

00:02:38.740 --> 00:02:41.520
And part of that is my technical
ability to do voice over.

00:02:41.520 --> 00:02:45.630
And part of it is showing
up 15 minutes early,

00:02:45.630 --> 00:02:47.163
being professional,
all that sort

00:02:47.163 --> 00:02:51.809
of stuff, which does kind
of seem like A for effort.

00:02:51.809 --> 00:02:52.350
I don't know.

00:02:52.350 --> 00:02:53.100
What do you think?

00:02:53.100 --> 00:02:54.420
CHRIS BOEBEL: Well.

00:02:54.420 --> 00:02:56.900
So I've had to think
about this a lot

00:02:56.900 --> 00:02:58.750
for the course I teach at MIT.

00:02:58.750 --> 00:03:01.532
And it's a huge,
huge issue because,

00:03:01.532 --> 00:03:02.990
so who should get
the better grade?

00:03:02.990 --> 00:03:07.010
The person who has a huge
amount of talent and experience

00:03:07.010 --> 00:03:10.840
as a filmmaker and
video maker, sluffs it,

00:03:10.840 --> 00:03:14.090
just like lays back
throughout the whole course,

00:03:14.090 --> 00:03:16.510
but does a really
nice piece at the end.

00:03:16.510 --> 00:03:18.820
Or the person who never
has done it before,

00:03:18.820 --> 00:03:20.530
doesn't necessarily
have a whole lot

00:03:20.530 --> 00:03:23.670
on the ball, when it
comes to media production,

00:03:23.670 --> 00:03:25.670
but just works and works
and works and comes out

00:03:25.670 --> 00:03:28.640
with something that's
kind of mediocre.

00:03:28.640 --> 00:03:32.550
Just because by the nature of
it having never done it before.

00:03:32.550 --> 00:03:33.610
That's really the issue.

00:03:33.610 --> 00:03:36.140
When you're dealing
with non-professionals--

00:03:36.140 --> 00:03:37.640
because I completely
agree with him,

00:03:37.640 --> 00:03:39.015
it's the Woody
Allen thing right?

00:03:39.015 --> 00:03:41.680
Like most of life is showing up.

00:03:41.680 --> 00:03:43.330
And it's totally true.

00:03:43.330 --> 00:03:47.810
But when you're dealing with
this huge, huge learning curve,

00:03:47.810 --> 00:03:49.220
it becomes very, very tricky.

00:03:49.220 --> 00:03:51.910
So what we do, we don't
do quite A for effort.

00:03:51.910 --> 00:03:56.070
But we do kind of allow an out
if your final project, which

00:03:56.070 --> 00:03:58.990
is a big part of your grade,
goes completely haywire

00:03:58.990 --> 00:04:00.970
and just falls apart
on you, you can

00:04:00.970 --> 00:04:04.440
write a fairly
substantial paper that

00:04:04.440 --> 00:04:07.270
describes what your intents
were or what your thought

00:04:07.270 --> 00:04:08.784
process was, what
went wrong, why

00:04:08.784 --> 00:04:10.950
it went wrong, what you
would have done differently.

00:04:10.950 --> 00:04:15.950
And so, essentially, you do have
a way supplementing or making

00:04:15.950 --> 00:04:18.130
up for this innate
problem you had,

00:04:18.130 --> 00:04:20.671
which was that you didn't know
what the hell you we're doing.

00:04:22.100 --> 00:04:24.341
Which is a problem.

00:04:24.341 --> 00:04:27.203
JOSHUA GUNN: It's
fairy innate for me.

00:04:27.203 --> 00:04:29.590
ELIZABETH CHOE: For all of us.

00:04:29.590 --> 00:04:32.920
Well, two of the course
values were challenge,

00:04:32.920 --> 00:04:34.770
and a lot of that
manifested in the rubric

00:04:34.770 --> 00:04:37.260
in the final project and
the graded assignments,

00:04:37.260 --> 00:04:41.060
as is their improvement
from the previous iteration?

00:04:41.060 --> 00:04:44.450
Is this person going outside
of their comfort zone?

00:04:44.450 --> 00:04:46.390
And then thoughtfulness.

00:04:46.390 --> 00:04:50.010
Can you tell that this
person has integrated

00:04:50.010 --> 00:04:52.750
some of the things we talked
about in class, whether it's

00:04:52.750 --> 00:04:57.140
through their blog posts,
or just like office hour

00:04:57.140 --> 00:04:58.820
reflections, things like that.

00:04:58.820 --> 00:05:01.970
So that was built
into the final grades,

00:05:01.970 --> 00:05:06.180
but then I would also say that
the graded sort of quality

00:05:06.180 --> 00:05:09.890
projects, and the
daily reflections

00:05:09.890 --> 00:05:12.770
were weighted pretty
equally so that if you

00:05:12.770 --> 00:05:17.110
had a student, which we
did, who had the skills,

00:05:17.110 --> 00:05:20.190
but didn't do the daily
blogs, their grade would

00:05:20.190 --> 00:05:21.250
suffer a little bit more.

00:05:21.250 --> 00:05:24.640
Just as much as someone
who did the daily blogs,

00:05:24.640 --> 00:05:30.950
and just could not
host for instance.

00:05:30.950 --> 00:05:37.360
In the end it worked out
by doing it that way.

00:05:37.360 --> 00:05:41.420
All the students who
I thought deserved

00:05:41.420 --> 00:05:45.540
great grades, because I knew
they worked really hard,

00:05:45.540 --> 00:05:47.120
got good grades.

00:05:47.120 --> 00:05:51.560
And all the students who
were very technically skilled

00:05:51.560 --> 00:05:53.990
still got decent
grades, but it wasn't

00:05:53.990 --> 00:05:55.240
like they got 100 or anything.

00:05:57.810 --> 00:05:59.394
It's always a tough
challenge, though.

00:05:59.394 --> 00:06:00.851
GEORGE ZAIDAN: My
math teacher used

00:06:00.851 --> 00:06:03.360
to say-- we'd be like, how are
you going to grade this test.

00:06:03.360 --> 00:06:06.540
He'd be like, well I'm going to
blindfold myself, turn around

00:06:06.540 --> 00:06:08.092
and throw darts behind my back.

00:06:08.092 --> 00:06:09.050
And we were like, good.

00:06:09.050 --> 00:06:09.554
That's good.

00:06:09.554 --> 00:06:10.970
CHRIS BOEBEL: I
just which I could

00:06:10.970 --> 00:06:13.450
have written a paper in
chemistry class in college

00:06:13.450 --> 00:06:15.174
to make up for the--

00:06:15.174 --> 00:06:16.840
GEORGE ZAIDAN: My
experiment went south.

00:06:16.840 --> 00:06:18.282
And here's what happened.

00:06:18.282 --> 00:06:20.240
ELIZABETH CHOE: It's hard
because MIT students,

00:06:20.240 --> 00:06:22.980
they want to know what
do I need to do to--

00:06:22.980 --> 00:06:24.010
CHRIS BOEBEL: Exactly.

00:06:24.010 --> 00:06:27.394
People are very focused on
achievement and doing well.

00:06:27.394 --> 00:06:28.810
ELIZABETH CHOE:
Which is why I was

00:06:28.810 --> 00:06:31.759
very conscious of by creating as
specific of a rubric as I can.

00:06:31.759 --> 00:06:33.300
JOSHUA GUNN: That
makes lot of sense,

00:06:33.300 --> 00:06:38.890
especially as you said before,
because this is a form of art,

00:06:38.890 --> 00:06:41.232
and there is no right or
wrong answer, so how do you--

00:06:41.232 --> 00:06:42.940
ELIZABETH CHOE: But
you can tell someone,

00:06:42.940 --> 00:06:46.220
look you didn't change
anything from your first draft.

00:06:46.220 --> 00:06:49.230
So you're going to get docked
for points on challenge,

00:06:49.230 --> 00:06:51.900
as the rubric says.

00:06:51.900 --> 00:06:54.610
Or you straight up didn't
do a blog reflection

00:06:54.610 --> 00:06:57.740
so you're getting a
zero on that section.

00:06:57.740 --> 00:06:59.370
But at least I do
think that there

00:06:59.370 --> 00:07:01.150
has to be something
tangible to go back

00:07:01.150 --> 00:07:05.660
to that you can't just sort
of arbitrarily assign a grade.

00:07:05.660 --> 00:07:08.220
I will say that, at
the end of the day,

00:07:08.220 --> 00:07:09.840
an assessment, a
great assessment,

00:07:09.840 --> 00:07:11.660
should be a reflection.

00:07:11.660 --> 00:07:15.690
Or should be there to
help students improve.

00:07:15.690 --> 00:07:19.910
And I do think that the value
in assessment and feedback

00:07:19.910 --> 00:07:22.910
came from just sort of one
on one, when you all worked

00:07:22.910 --> 00:07:25.357
with the students directly.

00:07:25.357 --> 00:07:27.940
And that's something that's not
captured on the OpenCourseWare

00:07:27.940 --> 00:07:28.980
class.

00:07:28.980 --> 00:07:33.370
But I would stay with
Jamie and our TA Siri,

00:07:33.370 --> 00:07:35.989
for at least two hours
every day after class,

00:07:35.989 --> 00:07:37.030
just talking to students.

00:07:37.030 --> 00:07:38.320
And you work with them.

00:07:38.320 --> 00:07:42.090
And when you and John
came to do the workshop,

00:07:42.090 --> 00:07:45.130
you'd just have direct
interaction with the students.

00:07:45.130 --> 00:07:49.670
I really think that's where
the most value came from.

00:07:49.670 --> 00:07:51.630
I don't know how you
all feel about that.

00:07:51.630 --> 00:07:54.130
CHRIS BOEBEL: I thought that
workshop was great, by the way.

00:07:54.130 --> 00:07:56.750
I didn't get a chance to
tell you, it was really nice.

00:07:56.750 --> 00:07:58.500
JOSHUA GUNN: I mean,
